General information about dataset The dataset is related to white variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine.

The dataset has 4898 observations for 14 variables. One variable (x) is for numeration, 12 input variables include objective tests and the output variable ‘quality’ is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts). There are no missing values in the dataset.

Input variables. Fixed acidity (tartaric acid - g / dm^3): most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile

Volatile acidity (acetic acid - g / dm^3): the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste. In our dataset we have range from 0.08 to 1.1 with 50% of wines to be in range 0.21 to 0.32

Citric acid (g / dm^3): found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines. In our dataset we have range from 0 to 1.66.

Residual sugar (g / dm^3): the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter. Wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet. In our dataset we have range from 0.6 to 65.8. We can explore this variable in details.

Chlorides (sodium chloride - g / dm^3): the amount of salt in the wine

Free sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

Total sulfur dioxide (mg / dm^3): amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine. In our dataset we have range from 9 to 440, which is much higher than 50, so we can explore this variable.

Density (g / cm^3): is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content In our dataset we have range from 0.9871 to 1.0390. Indeed, it is close to the density of water (1.0)

PH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale In our dataset we have range from 2.72 to 3.82, which is really close and most probably will have no difference.

Sulphates (potassium sulphate - g / dm3): a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, which acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant. In our dataset we have range from 0.22 to 1.08

Alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine In our dataset we have range from 8.0 to 14.2 It is rather wide range for wine, so we can explore this variable in details.

Output variable: Quality (score between 0 and 10) In our dataset we have range from 3 to 9 with 50% of observations to lay between 5 and 6.

Univariate Plots Section

Explore distribution of quality

We can see that most of our wines (about 50%) have quality 6, many wines are 5 and 7, few wines are 3, 4, 8 and 9. Quality is a discrete variable, but we can see its distribution is close to normal, there are no outliers and no gaps in the distribution, but poor and high quality wines are few.

Explore distribution of residual sugar - sweetness of wine

The distribution of residual sugar is right-skewed, with most of the values to be under 20. Values which are more than 20 are few. Let’s take a look at them closely:

There is only one wine with sugar content around 66, all others are under 33. This observation is an outlier, and I will remove it from my dataset.

## [1] 4897   13

As we can see, now there are 4897 observations in our dataset.

Now we can group our wines into categories depending on residual sugar. According to EU regulation 753/2002, the following terms may be used on the labels of table wines and quality wines: Dry - up to 4 g/l, if balanced with suitable acidity - up to 9 g/l Medium Dry - up to 12 g/l, if balanced with suitable acidity - up to 18 g/l Medium- up to 45 g/l Sweet - more than 45 g/l Let’s consider, that our wines are balanced, and use levels 9 g/l and 18 g/l for groupping the wines. New variable will take the name ‘category’.

As mentioned before, most of the wines are dry, and it is normal for south-european wines.

Explore alcohol content distribution

The distribution of alcohol is slightly right skewed, without long tail, but with big difference on the left side. In the beginning of the x-scale there are only few observations, then a gap, then again only few, and then bins are high with 100, 200 and more observations. This abrupt end can possible have influence for our visualizations, so we need to keep it in mind in future explorations. From the other side, I would not like to delete it as it is not an outlier, and it’s value is normal for wines.

Explore pH distribution

PH is normally distributed, its range is narrow and very common for wines, so we can consider that all our wine has normal pH levels and won’t explore it deeper.

Explore volatile acidity distribution

Distribution of volatile acidity is slightly right-skewed. We could say, that it is normally distributed till approx. 0.5 and then has a tail. It happens to be range of 0.6 to 0.9 of volatile acidity, which the human threshold can detect. Volatile acidity imparts a racy, balsamic edge to a wine. I will explore the impact of this variable on quality in later analysis.

Explore total sulfur dioxide distribution

We can see normal distribution for this variable. In later analysis we will check if it has any influence on the quality.

Explore density distribution

We can see normal distribution of this variable.

So, the scatterplot confirms the negative correlation between the alcohol and density for the whole dataset and for every category as well. Also we can see, that wines which are sweeter have higher density, for the same alcohol value.

Let’s also create multiple scatterplots to check, if this relationship between alcohol and density changes for quality of wine.

Some of the scatterplots have few observations, because very good and very poor wines are not many in our dataset, but all the scatterplots clearly show the same relationship between variables, so it is not corellated with the quality of wine.

This plot shows the relation between alcohol, residual sugar and density. There is a positive correlation between density and residual sugar. Corellation between alcohol and density is negative. On the visualization we can see 2 almost straight lines, each one of them “breaks” at the same point, changing (slightly or more) the inclination. This point is the density of 1.00, the density of clear water. The wine with this density will have a mean alcohol of 9.5 and the mean residual sugar 12.

Let’s explore the relation between descrete variable quality and 2 continuous variables: alcohol and residual sugar, by creating boxplots.

# Adding 2 y-axis on the plot
# Transforming y-axe for sugar by /3, so lines create better visualization.
ggplot(wine_new, aes(x = factor (quality) )) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y= alcohol, color = 'alcohol') ) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y = residual.sugar/3, color = 'Sugar') ) +
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*3, name = "Residual Sugar")) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("blue", "red")) +
  labs(y = "Alcohol", x = "Quality", colour = "Parameter")

As we can see, wines with low quality (3-4) do not have clear relationship with alcohol or sugar. One of the reasons for this can be actually a quality itself. If experts decided that these wines were bad, wine could be not balanced and have too little sugar (not good grapes), or have added sugar, or have added alcohol. Wines with average and above quality have visible trends. Wines with higher quality have less sugar and more alcohol.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows the relation between quality and alcohol. We see that wines with higher persentage of alcohol are more likely to have higher quality. Red smoother line is showing this tendention.

Alpha = 0.05 is used here to avoid overlapping, and jitter is used for the same reason, as quality variable is discrete. So we can also see distribution of wines in our dataset. Most of the wines have quality 5 and 6, less wines have quality 7, and much less wines have lower or higher quality.

Also we can see that almost all the wines contain 9 to 13% of alcohol, with the biggest part to be 9-11%, which is the most common alcohol level for white european wines.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot shows relationship between density and alcohol. We can see negative correlation between these variables, which is explained by the nature of making alcohol drink. Density of water is 1.0 and density of clear alcohol is 0.783. So the higher volume alcohol has in the water-alcohol mix, the lower will be the density of this mix. Coloring the plot by wine category we also add the sugar content into this relationship. We can see, that general negative corellation is the same within every category, but the most interesting thing we see - that wines with the same alcohol content will have higher density if they are have more sugar. F.e. for alcohol content of 9% dry wines will have density approx 0.993 to 0.997, medium dry 0.996 to 1.001 and medium 0.998 to 1.002.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot shows the relation between quality and 2 values: residual.sugar and alcohol.

We can split visualization into 2 parts. First part - wines with low quality (3-4). They do not have clear relationship with alcohol or sugar. One of the reasons for this can be actually a quality itself. If experts decided that these wines were bad, wine could be not balanced and have too little sugar (not good grapes), or have added sugar, or have added alcohol. Second part - Wines with average and high quality (5-9). Here we can see clear positive correlation for alcohol and negative correlation for sugar. Wines with higher quality have less sugar and more alcohol.

Reflection

During the analysis I made I experienced several important moments.

It is very important to explore individual variables and their distribution before exploring relationships.

If a dataset is not big enough, there may be too few observations in some parts, so the exploration will not be reliable. F.e. in my dataset we had only one observation for sweet wine. Deffinitely, you can’t rely on it for making decisions about category.

Sometimes the visualizations you choose may not reflect the correlation (maybe it is a wrong type of plot or wrong binwidth). So it is important not to make decision from the first plot, but to try different techniques - reduce overplotting, transform variables, and to apply condition summaries. Statistics matter.

The dataset may not always allow us to make a model, because there can be other variables, which influence the output, but they are not in your dataset. The quality of wine depends very highly on the quality of grapes, on the type of grapes and on the age of the wine. We knew nothing about this. It would be nice, if we could have some of this information to explore it and to try to make a model depending on it.

I had some struggles. It is not easy to find the correct way to visualize the data. Making wrong plot may lead to mistakes in interpretation of relationships. In our dataset I had to work with different types of data (categorical, discrete, continuous), each of them needed special approach.

But I was happy when I found the trends and was able to interpretate them. It is nice to start with exploring distribution and then to end with multivariable analysis. It was interesting to see the relationship between alcohol and quality or explore different variables through categories, which I decided to create.
